<?php $cat = "Engineer's Corner";$catlink = "engineers.php";$cat2 = "Buffing Wheel Hints";$cat2link = "engineers-buffinghints.php";$cat3 = "Buffing Wheel Flanges - Safety";$cat3link = "engineers-flanges.php";$title = "Buffing Wheel Flanges - Safety";$description = "buffing wheels, buffing, buff, buffing wheel flanges, safety";include_once ('includes/header.php'); ?>        <div class="content">    	<div class="col-left">        	<?php include_once ('includes/breadcrumbs.php'); ?>        	<h1><?php echo $title; ?></h1>            <img src="images/flanges-1.gif" width="188" height="154" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />            <p>The flanges on a buffing wheel help provide structure to the buffing cloth and provide integrity of the buff when pressure is applied by the work piece. The flanges holding the buff should press against the outer edge of the teeth on the clinch ring.</p>                        <p>Pressure from the flanges on the ends of the teeth will ensure a safer more even wearing buff.</p>                        <div class="divide">            	<img src="images/flanges-2.gif" width="133" height="80" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />                <p>SIMILARLY, when a crocodiles mouth is clamped over the end TEETH, he can't open his mouth and release the material he holds.</p>                <img src="images/flanges-3.gif" width="133" height="80" alt="Flanges" class="photo" style="clear:both;" />                <p>BUT... clamp him anywhere else and... The same is true of incorrectly clamped buffs... and the buffs can be JUST as dangerous...</p>            </div>                        <p><strong>Common Mistakes With Buffing Wheel Flanges:</strong></p>            <div class="divide">            	<img src="images/flanges-4.gif" width="101" height="142" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />                <p><strong>Mistake #1: Flanges not used</strong></p>                <p>This forces pressure from the nuts on the weakest part of the buffing wheel.</p>            </div><!--divide-->                        <div class="divide">            	<img src="images/flanges-5.gif" width="120" height="186" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />                <p><strong>Mistake #2: Flanges are too large</strong></p>                <p>This forces pressure on to the cloth material which may reduce the life span of the buff and poses.</p>            </div><!--divide-->                        <div class="divide">            	<img src="images/flanges-6.gif" width="109" height="151" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />                <p><strong>Mistake #3: Flanges are too small</strong></p>                <p>This forces pressure from the nuts on the weakest part of the buffing wheel and is as bad as having no flanges at all.</p>            </div><!--divide-->                        <img src="images/flanges-7.gif" width="162" height="217" alt="Flanges" class="photo" />            <p><strong>Correct Flanges</strong></p>            <p>For a contoured buff, center sections must be the same diameter to maintain pressure between the flanges.</p>        </div><!--col-left-->                <div class="col-right">        <?php include_once ('includes/r-engineer.php'); ?>        <?php include_once ('includes/hp-right.php'); ?>	        </div><!--col-right--><?php include_once ('includes/footer.php'); ?>        